<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
<script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>
<script src="search.js" defer></script>
<!-- MathJax for LaTeX formulas -->
<script>
  window.MathJax = {
    tex: {
      inlineMath: [['\(','\)'], ['$', '$']],
      displayMath: [['\[','\]']]
    },
    svg: { fontCache: 'global' }
  };
</script>
<script id="MathJax-script" async src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/mathjax@3/es5/tex-chtml.js"></script>
<link rel="preload" href="/assets/js/mobile-menu.js" as="script">
<link rel="preload" href="/assets/js/page-enhancements.js" as="script">

</head>
<body>

<main class="container" id="main-content">
<section>
<p>This calculator is designed for software engineers who need to analyze the complexity of their code using Halstead metrics. It provides an interactive tool to calculate key metrics and improve code quality.</p>
</section>
<section aria-labelledby="calculator-heading" class="calculator-container">
<h2 id="calculator-heading">Calculator</h2>
<div class="form-group">
<label for="operators">Number of Operators *</label>
<input aria-required="true" class="form-control" id="operators" type="number"/>
</div>
<div class="form-group">
<label for="operands">Number of Operands *</label>
<input aria-required="true" class="form-control" id="operands" type="number"/>
</div>
<button onclick="calculateMetrics()" type="button">Calculate</button>
</section>
<section class="results-container">
<h3>Results</h3>
<div id="results"><!-- Results will be displayed here --></div>
</section>
<section>
<h2>Authoritative Data Source</h2>
<p>All calculations are based on Halstead's metrics as described in the original publication <a href="https://github.com/aametwally/Halstead-Complexity-Measures" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">here</a>. All calculations are rigorously based on the formulas and data provided by this source.</p>
</section>
<section>
<h2>The Formula Explained</h2>
<div class="formula-box">
<p>Volume = (Operators + Operands) * log2(Operators + Operands)</p>
</div>
</section>
<section>
<h2>Glossary of Variables</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Operators:</strong> The unique operators in the code.</li>
<li><strong>Operands:</strong> The unique operands in the code.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section>
<h2>How It Works: A Step-by-Step Example</h2>
<p>Assume you have 20 operators and 30 operands, the volume is calculated as follows: Volume = (20 + 30) * log2(20 + 30).</p>
</section>
<section>
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
<div>
<h3>What are Halstead metrics?</h3>
<p>Halstead metrics are a set of software metrics introduced by Maurice Halstead to measure software complexity.</p>
<h3>How do these metrics help in software development?</h3>
<p>They provide insights into the complexity and maintainability of software code.</p>
</div>
</section>

</main>
<script>
        function calculateMetrics() {
            const operators = parseInt(document.getElementById('operators').value, 10);
            const operands = parseInt(document.getElementById('operands').value, 10);
            if (isNaN(operators) || isNaN(operands)) {
                alert('Please provide valid numbers for operators and operands.');
                return;
            }
            const volume = (operators + operands) * Math.log2(operators + operands);
            document.getElementById('results').innerText = `Calculated Volume: ${volume.toFixed(2)}`;
        }
    </script>


